A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners are struggling to find the money needed to repair the decayed highway infrastructure, many are seeing a solution in the form of a small black box that sticks above the dashboard of your car.
The devices, which record every mile driven by a motorist and transmit the information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and government planning offices to reshape the obsolete funding system for major U.S. roads.
The generally uninterested sector of major axis planning suddenly provoked a heated debate and turbulent alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to pressure the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you’re traveling, and possibly the road you’re traveling on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress fail to agree on whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental turn.
This is truly essential for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, director general of the Southern California Association of Governments, which predicts the state will begin recording the miles driven by each California driver by 2025.
There will be a change in how we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded by the taxes Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don’t buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more than a mile with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transport policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a pay-per-mile system.
“This turns out to be the most logical alternative in the long run,” he said.
Wonks calls this the cost of mileage.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces urban liberals, as taxes could be used to change driving habits in a way that reduces congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set in the state's ambitious global warming laws.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), Chairman of the Transport Committee of the House of Representatives, said he also sees it as the most viable alternative in the long term.
Free market supporters of the Reason Foundation also appreciate the idea of paying drivers a mile.
“It’s not just a tax hanging in a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The movement is also backed by two former U.S. Transportation secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go on the pay-per-mile path.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that reportedly covered about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural lawmakers representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to work or to the city.
Nevertheless, many states and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the country’s most important experience.
These drivers will soon pay the state kilometre fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The City of New York is considering one.
Illinois is trying a test on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the U.S. East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is studying how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their car with an aircraft, drivers were concerned that the government could follow their slightest facts and gestures.
“The concerns about Big Brother and things like that are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads the Nevada Department of Transportation’s Strategic Performance Management.
It's not something people want.
At the start of the trial, the Nevada ACLU warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to transform these devices into full-fledged location devices.”
There is no need to build a huge and bulky technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily walkways and walkways.
Nevada is one of the few states now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car is traveling, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology led some state agencies to resort to a small California start-up called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to help motorists who pay taxes to states.
It sought to drill into the emerging car insurance market, in which drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices it tests have appealed to big-axis planners because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, downloaded periodically by modem.
“People will be more likely to do that if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major errors have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are far less costly ways and far less intrusive methods to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering different choices to motorists.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a flat rate based on the average number of miles driven by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxation device that would also be equipped to pay for parking fees, provide “pay-to-drive” insurance, and create a real-time speed dataset from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits that the system offers them,” said a document on urban planning.
However, some transport planners wonder if the whole debate about mileage is just a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission of the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-off or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gasoline, so everyone pays their fair share.
“There is no need to resort to radical surgery when you simply need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, the director of legislation and public affairs at the commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: four unreleased songs
The British musician did not end up surprised this year.
