This is a story that is not one of them.
And a story so old that it is now fixed: I first heard the bobard that “independence means passport control” more than 40 years ago.
Yet an interesting point has been forgotten in this interpretation of an old dusty tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow the instructions of Europe, in fact?
Why exchange the yoke of London for the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe is definitely deadlocked.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties opposing the EU or campaigning for the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and coming from nowhere, gathered nearly five million votes in the September federal elections and pulled the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the project of creating a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the carcass weighing on national economies through the accession to the single currency, has led many people to think that the Europe Project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments registering excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
Rather, the European system has imposed on its members exchange rates favourable to German exporters – which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe find themselves with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-à-vis Germany.
The only recourse is to make dark cuts in wages and public spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current budgetary and monetary problems, there is a deeper malaise related to productivity in Europe.
Following the “green” energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than the United States.
This is a redundant disadvantage in terms of costs, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All wage freezes in the world will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt roars, especially in France, one of the great leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport to its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the French economy in ruins.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s far-right party, the anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial partial election, returning the socialists to power in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot start from the principle that a split from the right will automatically favor the left.
What is Marine Le Pen doing with her new popularity among the French white working class?
It wants to use next year’s European elections to create a single anti-currency and anti-European bloc within the European Parliament.
If the anti-European parties are a good figure in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I think: very soon, the anti-European and anti-currency sentiment in Europe will unite and will eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will come back to something that will resemble more the free “Europe of the Nations (sovereign)” privileged by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies could retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will regain their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will make the eyes of the United States soft.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left to account in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of Little England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending walkers to Berlin and Brussels.
