At the annual American Academy of Pediatrics conference this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, a pedoendocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young Americans and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents — in general, that doesn’t indicate a rapid shift to full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as bulging of the breasts, hair under the arms and in the pubic area, and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age of the first rules over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age was 12 and a half, compared to 12 and a quarter in 1970.
“Once the breast has started to grow, it takes at least two or three years for the first menstrual periods to appear,” said Kaplowitz, also the author of “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test for how puberty will evolve.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered “early” when the development of the breast is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8 years.
In most cases, development slows down or stops – this is something a pediatrician can follow closely.
A faster progression may justify tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the appearance of the first menstrual periods and prevent other consequences: premature aging of bones that can slow growth and small size in adulthood.
The drug and hormonal treatment recommendations are based on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate and affective maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious with drugs but recognizes that “controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others.”
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don’t want their very young daughters to have their own periods.
“They fear the risk of pregnancy or even the way they’re going to handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her first menstrual period at the age of 10.
Even if there were signs and we had talked about the rules, she was not emotionally prepared.
She returned from school frightened and upset to be the first of her friends.
There are many theories brought to public knowledge about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages conveyed by the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach their puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the most credible hypothesis is that of the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study of girls aged 6 to 9 that linked the percentage of fat mass to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have hair on the face and in the younger pubic area, the trend towards real early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference emphasized the complexity of the subject.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common, even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be cautious about how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pedoendocrinologist working at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean having a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz said.
If you stay calm, your child will react well in general.
Girls with early puberty should be reassured that, even when it happens earlier than expected, the process is part of life.
