Currently, passengers have to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the plane’s doors are closed.
They are not supposed to re-ignite them until the plane reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the commander gives his green light.
Passengers are supposed to turn off their aircraft during the descent of the plane before landing and not re-ignite them until the plane has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during takeoffs, landings and ground rolling, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, said she was happy with the changes.
“Once the new policy is implemented safely – and we will work closely with carriers for that – it will be beneficial for everyone,” Glading said in a statement.
