And heavier devices like laptops will always have to be stored because they could hurt someone if they were flying through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also continue to be banned.
The regulatory authority for mobile phones belongs to the Federal Communications Commission and not to the FAA.
The FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during takeoff and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transport safety expert on CBS News, said mobile phones were still considered to be at risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could eventually create interference with navigational instruments, but because we know, according to the FCC, they could disrupt mobile phone antennas relays if they are used on board,” Rosenker said.
An industrial advisory committee set up by the FAA to examine the issue recommended last month that the government authorize a wider use of personal electronic devices.
The pressure on the FAA has increased in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Detractors such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there are no valid security reasons for these bans.
Restrictions are also increasingly difficult to apply as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that at least one-third of passengers forget to turn off their devices, or do so deliberately.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports of interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers were carrying FM radios, the high-tech gadget of the time.
New airliners rely much more on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand electronic interference and are approved by the FAA.
Airlines have been allowing their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruise altitudes for several years.
Aircraft modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airliners are expected to allow wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit much lower power radio transmissions than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, only emit minimal transmissions when turning a page.
But transmissions are stronger when devices download or send data.
Amazon.com is among those pushing for easing restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers.
In 2011, the company’s executives loaded a line plane from Kindle e-book readers and stolen it to see if there were any problems, but there were none.
This has given the members of the FAA Advisory Committee mixed feelings as to whether or not the use of the devices presents a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed interference from the aircraft was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee stated that there are only anecdotal reports from pilots that indicate that aircraft can interfere with an aircraft's systems, and that most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to ask passengers to turn off their aircraft during landings at instruments in low visibility conditions.
