The single market has caused general discontent, with companies saying that the cost of the Brussels regulation is disproportionate to the benefits of being part of the European trade area – 40% of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European, even agree.
Finally, and even more so, our survey of business leaders revealed that a large majority wanted Britain to pursue initiatives in favour of a treaty change and the development of a trade-based relationship with the EU rather than a policy-based one.
This finding, which can be found in all major groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the corporate world is insisting on a “significant change” that returns power to the UK.
The stakes are high – succeeding in changing the treaty and better representing Britain’s interests would see a 16% turnaround of votes in favour of maintaining the country in the EU during a referendum.
