How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
Are you finished typing passwords to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will make it possible to verify the identity of a person performing transactions in a universe as transverse and transnational as the Internet.
Organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but worry about it.
Only in 2011 and in France, the Commission Nationale de l’Informatique et des Libertés has authorised 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, of the shape of the hand or of the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere, anytime,” said Justin Brookman, consumer privacy officer at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its limitations.
"For example, some people who work concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible," says Philippe Robin, Technical Director of Identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - we cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a drawback: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for about twenty years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
Due to the increased accuracy of the sensors and the computational capacity of the computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and the Netherlands have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and unfalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers forensic police services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognising a person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who he claims to be).
The identification so far concerned the issuance of identity documents: it is necessary to compare the biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) with the information that the State has on all citizens already filed.
This ensures that one person does not attempt to usurp someone else’s identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
“We retrieve images from surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet,” explains Dany Nassif, NEC France’s commercial development manager for biometric identification solutions.
Other use: take a photo of a quidam who is queuing in a store, track its progression thanks to facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logical (opening of a computer).
More recently, presence control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the buddy pointing for another," justifies Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also affect transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing their card and placing their hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the keystroke of the secret code.
A similar technique is being tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in store with your bank card, the customer does not type his code, but enters his finger in a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in cash thirty seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you tailor-made options.
And finally, rest assured by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is locked if you try to move it,” says Philippe Robin, of Thales.
But, in the absence of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
Specialists in the protection of privacy, they, continue to worry.
“The advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick, of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
