Scientists have just highlighted how a dog’s tail movements are related to his mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs stirred their tails more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs stirred their tails more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are differently involved in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what was wrong with other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to other dogs’ disordered tail movements, the researchers followed animals watching movies where other dogs appeared.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will probably not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with films featuring other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusing factor – and we were able to traffic the tail movement and present it as going more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw a dog without expression stirring the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog stirring the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they noticed a tail diverting mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog shaking the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs deliberately communicated with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: “If you encounter other dogs repeatedly and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tails to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side results in a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
Researchers say the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better grasp their animals’ emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol’s School of Veterinary Sciences, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs would go more easily to a robot dog when his tail was stirring to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study.”
He indicated that the differences could come from the fact that the dogs participating in the different studies did not fully consider film animals or robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“While many elements, found in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why their tails sometimes move on one side and sometimes on the other.
