A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new bump dolphin species off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, responsible for the scientific mission at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Environments (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of dolphin surprise you?
That's good news, but I'm not particularly surprised.
Although species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis in the past, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge in the sciences of species classification.
Moreover, it is not impossible that these advances in genetics and molecular biology call into question the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are questioned due to advances in genetics.
In the same way, two species that are very close morphologically have been distinguished through genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
A decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific humpback dolphins and Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have distinguished four species.
Why is this an important discovery, as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had been known for a long time by the researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture arises in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local extinction of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered endangered or endangered depending on the number of individuals on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility of recovery from nearby stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, from which the population of the newly discovered species is derived, its stock has automatically become weaker, thus making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This brewing of genes limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
The marine environment is the least well-known environment.
It is preferable to send robots to Mars, rather than to know what lives in the Mariannes pit, just 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money on the search for life on other planets than we do on marine research, and it’s high time that that changes.
